==English==

===Etymology===
The term may have arisen from the Indian word for a hired thug, ''[[goonda]]''.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[thug]], a usually muscular henchman with very little intelligence (also known as a 'Hired Goon'). The term ''goon'' rose to prominence in this context thanks to frequent usage in [[Popeye]].
#Guardians of the Oglala Sioux Nation, thugs employed by the corrupt tribal chairman of [[Pine Ridge Indian Reservation]], Dick Wilson, during the 1970s.
#An ice [[hockey]] player who has very few skills other than fighting. The number of goons has decreased and today there are no pure goons in the [[NHL]], as more skilled [[enforcer]]-type players have replaced them.
# 'Goon Squads' - A mercenary thug hired by bosses to break strikes, also sometimes used by police departments to refer to specific police who suppress protests.
# Peter Sellers, Harry  Secombe, Spike Milligan and Michael Bentine in their role in the 1950s radio comedy programme '''[[The Goon Show]]'''

